<!-- About Project Modal -->
<div class="modal fade" id="aboutProjectModal" tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true">
  <div class="modal-dialog modal-lg modal-dialog-centered modal-dialog-scrollable">
    <div class="modal-content about-modal">

      <div class="modal-header">
        <h5 class="modal-title">
          Development of Comprehensive Change & Encroachment Detection System
          using Geospatial Technology for Assam–Nagaland Interstate Border
        </h5>
        <button type="button" class="btn-close" data-bs-dismiss="modal"></button>
      </div>

      <div class="modal-body">

        <p class="modal-intro">
          The project <strong>“Development of Comprehensive Change & Encroachment Detection System using Geospatial Technology for Assam–Nagaland Interstate Border”</strong> 
          focuses on scientific monitoring of land use and land cover changes along the interstate boundary using satellite and UAV-based geospatial technologies. 
          The system supports evidence-based border monitoring, change assessment, and decision support.
        </p>

        <h6>Background</h6>
        <p>
          The Assam–Nagaland interstate boundary extends approximately 512 km and includes multiple historically disputed sectors. 
          Recurring border disputes and encroachment concerns require a systematic, technology-driven monitoring framework using 
          multi-temporal satellite imagery, GIS analysis, and spatial databases.
        </p>

        <h6>Project Objectives</h6>
        <ul class="modal-list">
          <li>Map Land Use Land Cover (LULC) along the Assam–Nagaland border using a 2 km buffer on both sides</li>
          <li>Establish base-year LULC mapping from 1989 onward</li>
          <li>Perform temporal change detection at quarterly monitoring intervals</li>
          <li>Detect land transformation such as forest to settlement, agriculture, and other land uses</li>
          <li>Support encroachment and hotspot identification using high-resolution imagery</li>
        </ul>

        <h6>Data & Methodology</h6>
        <ul class="modal-list">
          <li>Use multi-source satellite data including IRS, Landsat, Sentinel-2, and ultra high-resolution imagery</li>
          <li>Minimum mapping unit of 25 sq.m for classification</li>
          <li>Image preprocessing including rectification, reprojection, and enhancement</li>
          <li>GIS-based overlay and temporal change detection analysis</li>
          <li>Optional UAV surveys for hotspot and disputed locations</li>
          <li>Use of ArcGIS, QGIS, and ERDAS Imagine for geospatial processing</li>
        </ul>

        <h6>System Components</h6>
        <ul class="modal-list">
          <li>Multi-year LULC mapping and change detection layers</li>
          <li>Geospatial database with temporal attributes</li>
          <li>Encroachment and built-up change assessment</li>
          <li>Interactive Web-GIS application for visualization and analysis</li>
        </ul>

        <h6>Deliverables</h6>
        <ul class="modal-list">
          <li>Base year (1989) and quarterly LULC change maps</li>
          <li>Integrated GIS database with metadata</li>
          <li>Web-GIS monitoring platform with query and analysis tools</li>
          <li>Analytical outputs, statistics, and monitoring reports</li>
        </ul>

        <h6>Implementation</h6>
        <p>
          The project is implemented as a geospatial technology initiative in support of interstate border monitoring, 
          using satellite data, GIS analysis, and web-based visualization systems for operational decision support.
        </p>

      </div>

